1 Academic Gender Gap

The main variable of focus in this essay is the academic gender gap of degree programs in Austria. This is understood as an uneven distribution of places in degree programs at universities between female and male students (no more genders are available within the available data set). The gap emerges if either more female or male students are enrolled in a specific program. This [@StatistikAustria_GenderStatistik]

1.1 Methodology

For investigating the academic gender gap we will focus on comparative statistics. The used data set was created by Statistik Austria [@StatistikAustria_UniStud] and downloaded via their database access STATCube.

In a first step the overall gender distribution will be explored across all studies and fields. Afterwards, the composition of the total population of students will be assessed by splitting them by the degree program that they visit. In the final section those dimensions will then be combined and the gender gap determined for each degree program.

1.2 The Data Set

The aforementioned data set holds information about the amount of students enrolled in types of academic degree programs (bachelor studies, masters studies, doctoral studies or diploma studies) and the academic field the degree is associated with (science or arts). The data is further divided into sex (female or male) and sorted by semester. The overall available variables therefore are as follows:

  • Semester: Represents time periods - e.g.summer semester 2021
  • Sex: Shared gender of a subgroup of students - female or male
  • Field: A broad differentiation between categories of academic disciplines - University of the sciences or University of the arts
  • Studies: The level of education - Bachelor studies, Master studies, Doctoral studies, or Diploma studies

1.3 Visualisation

To understand the development of the academic gender gap over time line charts will be used for analysing the different specified dimensions of academic education. Moreover, mostly leverage weighted regression lines will be used for displaying the trend instead of raw data lines, since academic years are split into two semester and typically more new students register for the winter semester and , which leads to a fluctuating levels of students in between two academic years. To avoid overplotting this simplification will be employed for the first section of this essay.

1.4 Data Preperation

This page holds the code that is used for preparing the data set.

# Function to convert semester strings to startdate of semester
semester_to_startdate <- function(semester) {
  if (grepl("winter semester", semester)) {
    year <- as.numeric(sub(".*([0-9]{4})/([0-9]{2}).*", "\\1", semester))
    return(as.Date(paste(year, "-10-01", sep="")))
  } else if (grepl("summer semester", semester)) {
    year <- as.numeric(sub(".*([0-9]{4}).*", "\\1", semester))
    return(as.Date(paste(year, "-03-01", sep="")))
  } else {
    stop("Unknown semester format")
  }
}

# Function to convert semester strings to academic year
semester_to_academic_year <- function(semester) {
  if (grepl("winter semester", semester)) {
    year_start <- as.character(sub(".*([0-9]{4})/([0-9]{2}).*", "\\1", semester))
    year_end <- as.character(sub(".*([0-9]{4})/([0-9]{2}).*", "\\2", semester))
    return(paste(year_start, "/", year_end, sep=""))
  } else if (grepl("summer semester", semester)) {
    year <- as.numeric(sub(".*([0-9]{4}).*", "\\1", semester))
    return(paste(year - 1, "/", sub("[0-9]{2}([0-9]{2})", "\\1", year), sep=""))
  } else {
    stop("Unknown semester format")
  }
}
read_csv(
    "data/table_austria_public_university_studies.csv",
     skip = 5,
     show_col_types = FALSE
  ) %>%
  slice_head(n = -10) %>%
  rename(
    Field = "University (Ebene +1)",
    Study = "Kind of study"
  ) %>%
  select(Semester, Sex, Field, Study, Number) %>%
  mutate(
    Sex = factor(Sex),
    Field = factor(Field),
    Study = factor(Study),
    Number = as.integer(round(Number))
  ) %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(
    AcademicYear = semester_to_academic_year(Semester),
    SemesterStart = semester_to_startdate(Semester)
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  relocate(AcademicYear, SemesterStart, .before = Semester) -> df

df %>%
  select(-Field) %>%
  summarise(Number = sum(Number), .by = c(SemesterStart, Sex, Study)) %>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = c(SemesterStart, Study), names_from = Sex, values_from = Number) %>%
  mutate(FM_Ratio = female / male) %>%
ggplot(aes(SemesterStart, FM_Ratio)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = Study)) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = Study, color = Study)) +

  labs(
    title = "Students female-male Ratio by Studies",
    x = "Semesters",
    y = "Ratio female-male students"
  ) +
  theme_R()

read.csv("data/table_austria_population_gender.csv", skip = 5) %>%
  slice_head(n = -5) %>%
  rename(
    Year = "Time.section",
    Gender = "Gender..2.",
    Agegroup = "Alter.in.15.Jahresgruppen"
  ) %>%
  select(Year, Gender, Agegroup, Number) %>%
  mutate(
    Yearend = as.Date(paste(Year, "-12-31", sep = "")),
    Gender = factor(Gender),
    Agegroup = factor(Agegroup),
    Number = as.integer(round(Number))
  ) %>%
  relocate(Yearend, .before = Gender) %>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = c(Year, Yearend, Agegroup), names_from = Gender, values_from = Number) %>%
  mutate(Ratio = female / male) -> dfAge
ggplot(dfAge, aes(Yearend, Ratio)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = Agegroup)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Agegroup)) +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = 1), linetype = "longdash") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 0, to = 4, by = 0.2), expand = expansion(0.2,0)) +
  labs(
    title = "Population female-male Ratio by Agegroup",
    x = "Years",
    y = "Ratio female-male population"
  ) +
  theme_R()

dfAge %>%
  filter(Agegroup != "75 plus years old" & Agegroup != "60 to 74 years old") %>%
ggplot(aes(Yearend, Ratio)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = Agegroup)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Agegroup)) +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = 1), linetype = "longdash") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 0, to = 4, by = 0.05), expand = expansion(0.2,0)) +
  labs(
    title = "Population female-male Ratio by Agegroup",
    subtitle = "Excluding population with age >= 60",
    x = "Years",
    y = "Ratio female-male population"
  ) +
  theme_R() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(margin = margin(0,0,5,0)),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(margin = margin(0,0,10,0)),
  )
